VALUES ('ca5fccc8-659f-401d-a550-10ecd9f0950c', 'Which choice best states the main idea of the text?', 'Within quantum biology, the codification of an oral repertoire has long been read as straightforward progress, a reading that a generation of émigré scholars—whose archives, only recently catalogued, complicate the received chronology—did much to entrench. What that account treats as decoherence, however, the observed regularity reframes: the apparent advance, far from being intrinsic, was conditioned by an institutional tunnelling that the standard narrative cannot model. Granting that the correlation is genuine, one must still resist the inference that it is causal, for the same configuration recurs but solely where a prior constraint happens to hold.', 'passage', '[{"id":"A","text":"Read as a whole, the passage advances a qualified central claim. The opening impression of straightforward progress is, in fact, the passage''s settled thesis —as the argument''s middle movement makes plain.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[False Lead] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."},{"id":"B","text":"Read as a whole, the passage advances a qualified central claim. A documented correlation is real but not causal, since the same pattern recurs where the supposed mechanism is absent —as the argument''s middle movement makes plain.","is_correct":true,"explanation":"Correct: its second sentence is the only one that satisfies the discriminating condition."},{"id":"C","text":"Read as a whole, the passage advances a qualified central claim. Because the pattern is causal, the institutional condition it produces must be its effect rather than its source —as the argument''s middle movement makes plain.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Reciprocal Error] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."},{"id":"D","text":"Read as a whole, the passage advances a qualified central claim. No correlation of this kind can ever, in any field, license a causal inference —as the argument''s middle movement makes plain.","is_correct":false,"explanation":"[Over-Extrapolation] Grounded in passage language but fails on a specific qualifier in its second sentence."}]'::jsonb, 'B', 'Logical Reconstruction:
Step 1: The opening sentence is a False Lead: the view the author complicates.
Step 2: The middle concedes the correlation is genuine.
Step 3: The final clause draws the non-obvious implication: genuine but non-causal.
Step 4: The thesis is the synthesis of concession and implication, not any single sentence.

